{
  "ADUs": {
    "ADU1": {
      "text": "Gilson showed that genuine philosophic developments did occur during the middle ages and that modern philosophy could hardly be understood without studying the works of the great scholastic doctors.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU2": {
      "text": "Gilson showed that differences among scholastic doctors were not mere details, that their differences were at the heart of their philosophies, and that least-common-denominator scholasticism was an invention of incompetent historians.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU3": {
      "text": "Gilson showed that Aquinas' philosophic thought is a genuine advance upon Aristotle's thought, not a mere baptism of it, and that the agreement of Aquinas' commentators with him in respect to conclusions masked their divergence from him in respect to fundamental principlesâ€”the reasons which are more characteristic of a philosophy than its conclusions.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU4": {
      "text": "Gilson emphasizes the necessity in the actual economy of salvation that matters which could be known by natural reason should be revealed.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU5": {
      "text": "Gilson argues that a Christian must believe in the existence of the Christian God, although the existence of a Prime Mover or a Necessary Being can be demonstrated.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU6": {
      "text": "Gilson argues that Aquinas did not need to prove the existence of God, since theology takes the existence of its subject matter for granted.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU7": {
      "text": "Gilson argues at length that the five ways do not embody any single philosophic viewpoint: 'It may not be easy or even possible to encompass all these demonstrations within the limits of one philosophy.'",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU8": {
      "text": "Gilson concludes the chapter by returning to the comparison of sacred doctrine to common sense; while admitting limits to this metaphor, Gilson insists on its validity in so far as the theologian sees that the determinations of God discovered by irreducibly diverse philosophies belong to a single object known as one only under the higher formality that specifies theological consideration.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU9": {
      "text": "Gilson's fifth chapter, 'The Essence of God,' is divided into four sections.",
      "label": "premise"
    },
    "ADU10": {
      "text": "Gilson argues that the notion of essence is maintained in application to God only to provide a point of reference for the negation of essence when God is posited as a beyond-essence, or pure act of being.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU11": {
      "text": "Gilson emphasizes his position that inasmuch as Aquinas is a theologian, the only analogy important for him is that of creatures to God.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU12": {
      "text": "Gilson emphasizes his position that for Aquinas all knowledge is theological inasmuch as it concerns the revealable.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU13": {
      "text": "Gilson emphasizes his position that for Aquinas essence is a possibility for being.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU14": {
      "text": "Gilson's notion of Christian philosophy designates a rational elaboration of the revealable which is knowable by natural reason; thus it can be compared to non-Christian philosophies in its subject matter but cannot be compared to them in its point of view.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU15": {
      "text": "Gilson has argued long and effectively against the view that there is nothing philosophically significant in the thought of the middle ages.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU16": {
      "text": "Gilson has shown conclusively that Christian philosophy was a historical reality which ought not to be ignored.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU17": {
      "text": "Gilson's present thesis concerning Christian philosophy goes beyond his amply-demonstrated earlier position.",
      "label": "claim"
    },
    "ADU18": {
      "text": "Gilson's notion of Christian philosophy is fundamental to his understanding of Aquinas' entire teaching.",
      "label": "claim"
    }
  },
